Output to `stdout` (which is the `FILE *` that `printf` writes to) is *buffered*. More specifically line-buffered (when connected to a terminal).

That means the output won&#39;t actually be written to the terminal unless the buffer is flushed, which happens on four conditions: The `FILE *` is closed, the buffer is full, there is a newline, or you explicitly flush it with the [`fflush`](https://en.cppreference.com/w/c/io/fflush) function.

For your use-case the best solution would be to call `fflush` in the loop before sleeping:

    for(const Node *current = local_head; current != NULL; current = current-&gt;next) {
        printf(&quot;%d -&gt; &quot;, current-&gt;value);
        fflush(stdout);  // Make sure the buffer is flushed and written to the terminal
        sleep(1);
    }

